
<!-- 
If you take a look at the "EllipticalGalaxyGenerator" class and compare it with
the "EllipticalGalaxyGenerator" tag below, you will notice that many of the 
fields in the class match the parameters listed inside the tag. All you need to 
do set those fields is to simply list the field name below, along with a value. 
The rest is done for you. You will also notice that some parameters inside the tag
below don't appear as fields inside the "EllipticalGalaxyGenerator" class. Actually,
they do, but you don't see them because they're inherited from the "GalaxyGenerator"
abstract superclass.

They only parameter below that is NOT found in either the "EllipticalGalaxyGenerator" 
class or its abstract superclass "GalaxyGenerator" is "sampleNumSystems." You can
see that the parameter is given the boolean value "true."

When instantiating a GalaxyGenerator, there are two options: either, you can specify
EXACTLY how many StarSystems you want the GalaxyGenerator to generate. Say you 
specify 1000 StarSystems to generate. This way, whenever you call the method "generate()"
on the GalaxyGenerator, a galaxy will be returned with 1000 StarSystems. The XML
code for this type of specification is below:

    <EllipticalGalaxyGenerator>
        <numSystems>       1000  </numSystems>
        <sampleNumSystems> false </sampleNumSystems>
    </EllipticalGalaxyGenerator>

Alternatively, let's say you DON'T want to specify exactly how many StarSystems 
to generate, and would rather generate a random number of galaxies. Let's say you 
want "about 1000 StarSystems, plus or minus 100." This type of specification can
be seen below:

    <EllipticalGalaxyGenerator>
        <numSystemsMean>   1000 </numSystemsMean>
        <numSystemsSD>     100  </numSystemsSD>
        <sampleNumSystems> true </sampleNumSystems>
    </EllipticalGalaxyGenerator>
    
Notice that the "sampleNumSystems" parameter has changed to true. Basically, 
"sampleNumSystems" set to "true" means choose a random number of StarSystems, and 
set to "false" means generate with a given number of StarSystems.

This pattern can also be seen in <SimpleStarSystemGenerator>, with the <sampleNumPlanets>
tag.
--> 

<config>
    
    <EllipticalGalaxyGenerator>
        <numSystemsMean>    10     </numSystemsMean>
        <numSystemsSD>      1      </numSystemsSD>
        <sampleNumSystems>  true    </sampleNumSystems>
        <minSystemDist>     210     </minSystemDist>
        <width>             1600   </width>
        <height>            900    </height>
        <xSD>               300    </xSD>
        <ySD>               200    </ySD>
        <xBound>            450    </xBound>
        <yBound>            450    </yBound>
    </EllipticalGalaxyGenerator>

    <SimpleStarSystemGenerator>
        <numPlanetsMean>    9       </numPlanetsMean>
        <numPlanetsSD>      2       </numPlanetsSD>
        <sampleNumPlanets>  true    </sampleNumPlanets>
        <planetSepMean>     100       </planetSepMean>
        <planetSepSD>       10       </planetSepSD>
        <minPlanetSep>      50       </minPlanetSep>
        <plutoDist>         1500     </plutoDist>      
        <starMassMean>      100     </starMassMean>  
        <starMassSD>        10      </starMassSD>
    </SimpleStarSystemGenerator>

    <SimplePlanetGenerator>
    </SimplePlanetGenerator>
    
    <JumpPointsGenerator>
        <connectBlackHoles>   false </connectBlackHoles>
        <threshold>           100    </threshold>
        <constant>            1     </constant>
    </JumpPointsGenerator>

</config>